article.description:
Fighting breast cancer, Edna Campbell returned to the court Tuesday night to help the Sacramento Monarchs beat the Seattle Storm 59-51 in the final game of the WNBA regular
season.
article.headline: Campbell returns to help Monarchs win

images.name: Campbell_Edna 020814 vtop
images.caption: Edna Campbell received a standing ovation as she returned to the court after battling breast cancer.

article.linkText: Fighting breast cancer, Campbell returns in Monarchs' finale
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Fighting breast cancer, Edna Campbell
returned to the court Tuesday night to help the Sacramento Monarchs
beat the Seattle Storm 59-51 in the final game of the WNBA regular
season.

<photo1>Undergoing radiation treatment following two surgeries and
months of chemotherapy, the 33-year-old guard scored four points on
2-for-5 shooting in 12 minutes. She was hugged by players from both
teams after the game.

	   Campbell received a standing ovation when she was introduced
before the game, and the fans stood again and cheered when she
entered the game early in the first half.

	   ''That noise the crowd made was love and support,'' Campbell
said. ''I was a little overwhelmed at first with the crowd behind
me. This was pretty memorable.''

	   Campbell scored her first basket late in the first half, making
a steal and dribbling the length of the court to bank a shot over
6-foot-4 Kamila Vodichkova.

	   Two minutes later, Campbell hit a shot from the corner, capping
a 16-0 run that gave the Monarchs a 31-15 lead.

	   ''Having Edna back was a big deal to everyone,'' teammate
Tangela Smith said. ''We were all excited to see her out there. It
was very emotional.

	   ''We wanted to win this one for Edna. She proved to everyone you
can come back from something that serious.''

	   Campbell, the first active WNBA player to be diagnosed with
breast cancer, received the WNBA Community Assist Award in July for
her outreach work.

	   ''I was happy about everything tonight. It's great to end the
season this way,'' Campbell said.

	   Yolanda Griffith had 19 points, and Smith added 17 for the
Monarchs (14-18), who nearly squandered the lead before pulling
away in the closing minutes to conclude the season by winning 10 of
their last 12 games.

	   Reserve center Simone Edwards scored 14 of her 18 points in the
second half for Seattle (17-15).

	   ''You saw how the fans reacted out there,'' Seattle coach Lin Dunn said. ''It was great to
see her back on the court. Basketball is her life.''

	   Vodichkova had 12 points, and Lauren Jackson added 11 points for Seattle, which won seven of their final nine games to clinch a
playoff berth.

	   ''I don't know if we ever approached a game like this before,''
Dunn said. ''It was a new experience for us. We wanted to play
hard, but we also wanted to rest people.''

	   Seattle, which secured its first playoff berth with a victory
Sunday night in Utah, will face defending champion Los Angeles in
the first round.
